description: Use subagents selectively for code-to-Figma component workflows
alwaysApply: true
---

# Figma Subagent Orchestration

- Apply this rule when the user asks to bring a code-backed component to the Figma canvas or update an existing Figma component from code.
- The main agent owns orchestration and chooses the lightest safe workflow for the request.
- Use the full workflow when any of the following are true:
  - creating a new component
  - changing composition model
  - introducing or reworking reusable child components
  - token reconciliation is nontrivial
  - dark mode or the full QA matrix materially matters
- Use the fast workflow only when all of the following are true:
  - updating an existing component
  - the code contract is already obvious
  - no slot or property ambiguity exists
  - no new child reuse decisions are needed
- Full workflow:
  1. `figma-code-contract`
  2. `figma-preflight`
  3. `figma-execution-planner`
  4. human approval
  5. `figma-implementation`
  6. `component-validator`
- Fast workflow:
  1. `figma-code-contract`
  2. `figma-preflight`
  3. compact planning in the main agent or a minimal `figma-execution-planner` pass
  4. `figma-implementation`
  5. targeted `component-validator` only when implementation reports risk, token substitution, dark-mode uncertainty, or QA ambiguity
- Responsibility boundaries:
  - `figma-code-contract`: code-only discovery
  - `figma-preflight`: Figma-context discovery and preflight, always using `docs/pallas-ui-component-mapping.md`, and owns the Figma inventory snapshot for the run
  - `figma-execution-planner`: approval-stage execution plan and downstream implementation handoff when full planning is required
  - `figma-implementation`: write path only, reusing the upstream inventory snapshot unless it is stale or contradicted
  - `component-validator`: report-only QA; if QA fails, return work to implementation
- Do not add extra discovery or implementation subagents unless the user asks or a blocker clearly requires escalation.
- Do not split the write path across multiple implementation subagents by default.
- `explore` and `generalPurpose` remain optional escalation tools for broad unknowns, not the default workflow.
- Cache Figma inventory between stages. Reuse existing pages, candidate component families, variable collections, and text styles from preflight instead of rediscovering them at each downstream step unless staleness or contradictory file state requires a refresh.
- If the component is ambiguous enough that correct modeling depends on unresolved human intent, stop and ask the user instead of adding more subagents.
